 This is a common issue with context menus - the right-click event often causes the text selection to be cleared before the context menu appears. Here are a few ways to fix this:

## Method 1: Prevent Selection Clearing on Right-Click

Add an event listener to prevent the default text deselection behavior:

```javascript
// Add this to your component or globally
useEffect(() => {
  const handleContextMenu = (e) => {
    // Prevent the default context menu and selection clearing
    if (window.getSelection().toString()) {
      e.preventDefault();
    }
  };

  document.addEventListener('contextmenu', handleContextMenu);
  return () => document.removeEventListener('contextmenu', handleContextMenu);
}, []);
```

## Method 2: Capture Selection Before Context Menu

Store the selection when the context menu is triggered:

```javascript
const [selectedText, setSelectedText] = useState('');

const handleContextMenu = (e) => {
  const selection = window.getSelection().toString();
  if (selection) {
    setSelectedText(selection);
    // Now you can use selectedText in your context menu actions
  }
};

// Apply to your trigger element
<div onContextMenu={handleContextMenu}>
  Your content here
</div>
```

## Method 3: Use CSS to Maintain Selection

Add CSS to prevent selection from being cleared:

```css
.preserve-selection {
  -webkit-user-select: text;
  -moz-user-select: text;
  -ms-user-select: text;
  user-select: text;
}

.preserve-selection::selection {
  background: #b3d4fc; /* Or your preferred selection color */
}
```

## Method 4: Shadcn-Specific Solution

If you're using shadcn's ContextMenu, you can modify the trigger behavior:

```jsx
<ContextMenu>
  <ContextMenuTrigger 
    onContextMenu={(e) => {
      // Capture selection before menu opens
      const selection = window.getSelection();
      if (selection.rangeCount > 0) {
        // Store the range to restore later if needed
        const range = selection.getRangeAt(0);
        // Store in ref or state for use in menu items
      }
    }}
  >
    Your content
  </ContextMenuTrigger>
  <ContextMenuContent>
    {/* Your menu items */}
  </ContextMenuContent>
</ContextMenu>
```

The most reliable approach is usually Method 2 - capturing the selected text when the context menu is triggered, since you'll likely want to use that text in your menu actions anyway (like "Copy", "Cut", etc.).

Which approach would work best for your specific use case?

